questions = [
  {"id":176,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"In the cloud shared responsibility model, who is responsible for patching the hypervisor in an IaaS environment?","options":{"A":"The customer","B":"The cloud service provider","C":"Both equally","D":"A third-party auditor"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"In IaaS, the cloud provider manages and patches the underlying infrastructure including hypervisors, physical hardware, and networking. The customer is responsible for OS, applications, and data.","A":"The customer is responsible for the OS and above in IaaS, not the hypervisor.","B":"Correct. The cloud provider owns and patches the hypervisor and physical infrastructure in IaaS.","C":"Responsibility for hypervisor patching is not shared; it belongs exclusively to the provider.","D":"Third-party auditors assess compliance; they don't patch infrastructure."}},
  {"id":177,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which cloud service model provides the LEAST customer control over the underlying infrastructure?","options":{"A":"IaaS","B":"PaaS","C":"SaaS","D":"FaaS"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"SaaS provides the least customer control — the provider manages everything from infrastructure to the application. Customers only control their data and user configuration.","A":"IaaS provides the most customer control, giving access to virtualized computing, storage, and networking.","B":"PaaS provides middleware and runtime environments; customers control applications but not infrastructure.","C":"Correct. SaaS gives customers only data and limited application configuration control.","D":"FaaS (Functions as a Service/serverless) is similar to PaaS with even less infrastructure control, but SaaS is the most restrictive for customers."}},
  {"id":178,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"A company runs services using small, independently deployable components that communicate via APIs. This architecture is called:","options":{"A":"Monolithic architecture","B":"Serverless computing","C":"Microservices","D":"Containerization"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Microservices architecture decomposes applications into small, loosely coupled services that communicate via APIs. Each service can be deployed, scaled, and updated independently.","A":"Monolithic architecture combines all functions in a single deployable unit.","B":"Serverless computing runs code in response to events without server management; it can host microservices but is a different concept.","C":"Correct. Independently deployable services communicating via APIs is the microservices pattern.","D":"Containerization is the packaging technology often used to run microservices; the architecture pattern is microservices."}},
  {"id":179,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which IoT security concern arises when devices are deployed with limited processing power that cannot run full-featured security software?","options":{"A":"Default credentials","B":"Resource constraints preventing security controls","C":"Lack of firmware updates","D":"Insecure APIs"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Many IoT devices have minimal CPU, memory, and storage, making it impossible to run traditional security software like antivirus, endpoint agents, or implement complex encryption — a fundamental IoT security challenge.","A":"Default credentials are a common IoT issue but are separate from resource constraint limitations.","B":"Correct. Resource constraints prevent IoT devices from implementing full security controls.","C":"Lack of firmware updates is a maintenance and lifecycle issue, distinct from resource constraints.","D":"Insecure APIs are a development issue, not directly related to device resource limitations."}},
  {"id":180,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which architecture model provides the MOST security control over data because all data and systems remain on premises?","options":{"A":"Public cloud","B":"Private cloud","C":"Hybrid cloud","D":"Community cloud"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"A private cloud (on-premises or dedicated hosted environment) gives organizations complete control over infrastructure, data, and security controls, as no resources are shared with other tenants.","A":"Public cloud shares infrastructure with other tenants, reducing direct security control.","B":"Correct. Private cloud provides maximum control since the organization owns and manages all resources.","C":"Hybrid cloud mixes public and private; control varies by workload placement.","D":"Community cloud shares resources among organizations with similar requirements; less control than private."}},
  {"id":181,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which security concern is UNIQUE to virtualized environments where multiple VMs share the same physical host?","options":{"A":"DDoS attacks","B":"VM escape","C":"Insider threats","D":"Password attacks"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"VM escape is a virtualization-specific vulnerability where an attacker breaks out of a guest VM to access the hypervisor or other VMs on the same physical host, a risk not present in non-virtual environments.","A":"DDoS attacks target any network-accessible service; not specific to virtualization.","B":"Correct. VM escape is a virtualization-specific attack that allows breaking out of the VM boundary.","C":"Insider threats exist in all environments; not specific to virtualization.","D":"Password attacks target any authentication system; not specific to virtualization."}},
  {"id":182,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"SCADA systems used in power grids present unique security challenges because they:","options":{"A":"Use the latest security protocols","B":"Were designed for safety and reliability in isolated environments, not internet-connected security","C":"Run on modern, patchable operating systems","D":"Are only accessible physically on-site"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"SCADA/ICS systems were designed decades ago for reliability and safety in air-gapped environments. They lack modern security features and were never designed for internet connectivity, creating significant security challenges when connected to IP networks.","A":"SCADA systems typically use legacy protocols without modern security features.","B":"Correct. SCADA systems prioritize operational reliability over security, creating risks when internet-connected.","C":"Many SCADA systems run on outdated, unpatchable operating systems (e.g., Windows XP).","D":"SCADA systems are increasingly network-connected for remote monitoring, expanding their attack surface."}},
  {"id":183,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"A DMZ is BEST described as a network segment that:","options":{"A":"Connects all internal departments to each other","B":"Hosts internet-facing services while separating them from the internal network","C":"Provides encrypted tunnels for remote employees","D":"Contains only backup servers"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"A DMZ (Demilitarized Zone) is a network segment that hosts internet-facing services (web servers, email servers) while isolating them from the internal network with firewalls on both sides.","A":"Internal connections between departments use the internal LAN, not a DMZ.","B":"Correct. A DMZ separates internet-facing services from the internal network using dual firewalls.","C":"VPNs provide encrypted tunnels; a DMZ is a network zone, not a tunneling technology.","D":"Backup servers are typically kept on internal, protected segments — not internet-facing DMZs."}},
  {"id":184,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which type of firewall can inspect the full content of application-layer traffic, including decrypting and inspecting HTTPS?","options":{"A":"Packet filtering firewall","B":"Stateful inspection firewall","C":"Next-generation firewall (NGFW)","D":"Circuit-level gateway"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Next-generation firewalls (NGFW) perform deep packet inspection (DPI) including application-layer analysis, SSL/TLS inspection, intrusion prevention, and application identification — capabilities beyond stateful inspection.","A":"Packet filtering only examines IP headers and ports; it cannot inspect application content.","B":"Stateful inspection tracks TCP state but does not perform deep application-layer inspection.","C":"Correct. NGFWs perform deep packet inspection including HTTPS decryption and inspection.","D":"Circuit-level gateways monitor TCP handshakes but don't inspect application data."}},
  {"id":185,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which network device operates at Layer 2 to separate broadcast domains and logically divide a physical network?","options":{"A":"Router","B":"VLAN-capable switch","C":"Load balancer","D":"Proxy server"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"VLANs (Virtual Local Area Networks) implemented on Layer 2 switches logically separate a physical network into distinct broadcast domains, providing network segmentation without requiring separate physical hardware.","A":"Routers operate at Layer 3 and separate networks, not logical Layer 2 broadcast domains.","B":"Correct. VLAN-capable switches create logical broadcast domain separation at Layer 2.","C":"Load balancers distribute traffic across servers; they don't create broadcast domains.","D":"Proxy servers intermediate client-server communications at the application layer."}},
  {"id":186,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which security device is placed inline on a network and actively blocks detected attacks?","options":{"A":"IDS","B":"IPS","C":"SIEM","D":"WAF"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"An Intrusion Prevention System (IPS) is placed inline in the network traffic path and actively blocks detected attacks. An IDS only detects and alerts without blocking.","A":"An IDS detects and alerts on attacks but is not inline and does not block traffic.","B":"Correct. IPS is inline and actively blocks detected malicious traffic.","C":"SIEM aggregates and analyzes security logs; it does not sit inline on the network.","D":"A WAF (Web Application Firewall) specifically protects web applications; IPS protects general network traffic."}},
  {"id":187,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which approach to network architecture combines software-defined networking with cloud-delivered security services to secure distributed workforces?","options":{"A":"MPLS","B":"SD-WAN","C":"SASE","D":"VPN concentrator"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"SASE (Secure Access Service Edge) combines networking (SD-WAN) with cloud-delivered security services (CASB, FWaaS, ZTNA) to securely connect users and devices regardless of location.","A":"MPLS is a private WAN technology without integrated cloud security services.","B":"SD-WAN provides software-defined WAN connectivity; it's a component of SASE but not the full framework.","C":"Correct. SASE integrates SD-WAN with cloud-delivered security in a unified service.","D":"A VPN concentrator aggregates VPN connections; it doesn't provide the cloud-native security integration of SASE."}},
  {"id":188,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"A forward proxy server is BEST used to:","options":{"A":"Distribute incoming requests across multiple backend servers","B":"Control and monitor outbound internet access from internal users","C":"Terminate TLS connections on behalf of backend servers","D":"Authenticate remote users before granting VPN access"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"A forward proxy sits between internal users and the internet, controlling outbound access, filtering content, caching responses, and anonymizing user requests to external servers.","A":"Distributing requests across backend servers is the role of a load balancer.","B":"Correct. A forward proxy controls internal user access to external internet resources.","C":"Terminating TLS on behalf of servers is a reverse proxy function.","D":"VPN authentication is handled by VPN gateways, not forward proxies."}},
  {"id":189,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which network security device provides a Web Application Firewall (WAF) capability?","options":{"A":"IPS","B":"NGFW","C":"WAF","D":"Both B and C"},"correct_answer":"D","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Both dedicated WAF appliances and modern NGFWs can provide WAF capabilities. NGFWs often include WAF functionality as part of their application-layer security features.","A":"A standard IPS does not typically include WAF-specific application inspection for HTTP/HTTPS at Layer 7 for web apps.","B":"NGFWs can include WAF functionality as part of deep packet inspection and application security.","C":"Dedicated WAF appliances specifically protect web applications.","D":"Correct. Both NGFWs and dedicated WAF appliances can provide web application firewall capabilities."}},
  {"id":190,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which device placement decision puts a security appliance between the internal network and the internet to inspect all traffic?","options":{"A":"Inline","B":"Passive tap","C":"Out-of-band","D":"Virtual"},"correct_answer":"A","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Inline placement positions the security device directly in the traffic path so all traffic passes through it, enabling active blocking. This is required for IPS, NGFW, and WAF functionality.","A":"Correct. Inline placement puts the device in the traffic path for inspection and blocking.","B":"A passive tap copies traffic for analysis without being in the path; it cannot block traffic.","C":"Out-of-band receives traffic copies and provides analysis but is not inline.","D":"Virtual refers to the form factor (software-based), not the placement mode."}},
  {"id":191,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Data that is currently being processed by a CPU (e.g., in RAM) is in which state?","options":{"A":"Data at rest","B":"Data in transit","C":"Data in use","D":"Data in archive"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Data in use refers to data that is actively being processed — in CPU registers, RAM, or cache. It is the most difficult state to protect because it must be decrypted to be processed.","A":"Data at rest is stored on disk or other storage media, not actively being processed.","B":"Data in transit is moving across a network.","C":"Correct. Data actively being processed in CPU/RAM is data in use.","D":"Data in archive is a subset of data at rest — stored long-term, not currently processed."}},
  {"id":192,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which data classification label would MOST likely apply to publicly available company marketing materials?","options":{"A":"Confidential","B":"Restricted","C":"Public","D":"Private"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":1,"explanations":{"correct":"Public data is intentionally released for public consumption. Marketing materials, press releases, and public websites contain public information.","A":"Confidential data is sensitive internal information with restricted access.","B":"Restricted data has the highest level of protection (e.g., trade secrets, classified).","C":"Correct. Publicly available marketing materials are classified as Public.","D":"Private data is internal to the organization but not for public release."}},
  {"id":193,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which encryption solution protects an entire storage drive, including the OS, and requires authentication before the OS boots?","options":{"A":"File-level encryption","B":"Database encryption","C":"Full disk encryption (FDE)","D":"Transport encryption"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Full Disk Encryption (FDE) encrypts the entire drive including the OS partition. Pre-boot authentication is required before the OS loads, protecting data if the drive is physically removed.","A":"File-level encryption protects individual files but not the OS or all files automatically.","B":"Database encryption protects stored database data; it doesn't cover the entire drive.","C":"Correct. FDE encrypts the entire drive and requires pre-boot authentication.","D":"Transport encryption (TLS/VPN) protects data in transit, not at rest on a drive."}},
  {"id":194,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"An organization must ensure that data stored in one country is not accessible from another country due to local laws. This is referred to as:","options":{"A":"Data sovereignty","B":"Data retention","C":"Data classification","D":"Data minimization"},"correct_answer":"A","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Data sovereignty refers to the principle that data is subject to the laws of the country where it is stored or processed. Organizations must comply with local data residency laws (like GDPR in the EU).","A":"Correct. Data sovereignty ensures data stays within jurisdictional boundaries to comply with local laws.","B":"Data retention defines how long data must be kept; not about geographic jurisdiction.","C":"Data classification assigns sensitivity levels; not related to geographic restrictions.","D":"Data minimization collects only necessary data; not about geographic storage restrictions."}},
  {"id":195,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which technology controls who can print, copy, or forward a sensitive document, even after it has been sent to a recipient?","options":{"A":"DLP","B":"Digital Rights Management (DRM)","C":"Encryption","D":"Data classification"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Digital Rights Management (DRM) applies persistent access controls to documents and media that follow the content, restricting actions like printing, copying, forwarding, or screenshots regardless of where the file goes.","A":"DLP prevents data from leaving the organization; it doesn't control usage after delivery.","B":"Correct. DRM enforces persistent usage restrictions that travel with the content.","C":"Encryption protects confidentiality in transit or at rest; it doesn't control usage permissions.","D":"Data classification assigns labels; it doesn't technically enforce usage restrictions."}},
  {"id":196,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"What does RPO (Recovery Point Objective) define?","options":{"A":"How quickly systems must be restored after failure","B":"The maximum acceptable data loss measured in time","C":"The minimum number of backup copies required","D":"The time required to test a disaster recovery plan"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"RPO defines the maximum amount of data loss an organization can tolerate, measured in time. If RPO is 4 hours, backups must occur at least every 4 hours so no more than 4 hours of data can be lost.","A":"How quickly systems must be restored is RTO (Recovery Time Objective).","B":"Correct. RPO defines the maximum acceptable data loss, measured in time since the last backup.","C":"Minimum backup copies is a related policy but not what RPO defines.","D":"DR plan testing frequency is not defined by RPO."}},
  {"id":197,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"What does RTO (Recovery Time Objective) define?","options":{"A":"The maximum acceptable amount of data that can be lost","B":"How often backups must be performed","C":"The maximum time allowed to restore a system after a failure","D":"The minimum backup retention period"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"RTO defines the maximum acceptable time it can take to restore a system or service after a failure. If RTO is 2 hours, the system must be operational again within 2 hours of a failure.","A":"Maximum acceptable data loss is defined by RPO, not RTO.","B":"Backup frequency is determined by RPO, not RTO.","C":"Correct. RTO is the maximum time allowed for system restoration after a disaster.","D":"Backup retention period is a data lifecycle policy, not RTO."}},
  {"id":198,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which backup type copies ALL data every time it runs, regardless of whether data has changed since the last backup?","options":{"A":"Incremental","B":"Differential","C":"Full","D":"Snapshot"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":1,"explanations":{"correct":"A full backup copies all selected data every time it runs, regardless of changes. It takes the most time and storage but provides the simplest restore — from a single backup set.","A":"Incremental backup copies only data changed since the last backup (full or incremental).","B":"Differential backup copies data changed since the last full backup.","C":"Correct. A full backup copies all data every run.","D":"A snapshot captures the state of a system at a point in time, often used in virtualization; it can be full or differential in nature."}},
  {"id":199,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"An organization wants to recover the most recent data after a failure with the fewest backup sets to restore. Which backup strategy BEST meets this requirement?","options":{"A":"Full backups only","B":"Full + incremental","C":"Full + differential","D":"Grandfather-Father-Son (GFS)"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":4,"explanations":{"correct":"Full + differential requires only two backup sets to restore (the last full + the last differential), providing quick recovery with relatively current data. Full + incremental requires many sets but uses less storage.","A":"Full backup only provides fast restore but requires the most storage and time to create.","B":"Full + incremental uses the least storage but requires the most sets to restore (full + every incremental since).","C":"Correct. Full + differential requires only two backup sets for a complete restore.","D":"GFS is a rotation scheme, not a backup type selection strategy."}},
  {"id":200,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which site type provides an alternate location with all infrastructure pre-configured, tested, and data replicated, enabling immediate failover?","options":{"A":"Cold site","B":"Warm site","C":"Hot site","D":"Mobile site"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"A hot site is a fully operational duplicate of the primary site with current data replication. It enables near-immediate failover (minutes to hours) but is the most expensive option.","A":"A cold site provides only basic infrastructure (power, network, space) — no equipment or data; recovery takes days to weeks.","B":"A warm site has hardware and connectivity pre-staged but may need data restoration; recovery takes hours to days.","C":"Correct. A hot site is fully operational with replicated data, enabling immediate failover.","D":"A mobile site is a portable facility (trailer/van) used for temporary recovery operations."}},
  {"id":201,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which RAID level provides both striping AND mirroring, offering fault tolerance AND improved performance?","options":{"A":"RAID 0","B":"RAID 1","C":"RAID 5","D":"RAID 10"},"correct_answer":"D","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"RAID 10 (1+0) combines mirroring (RAID 1) for fault tolerance with striping (RAID 0) for performance. It can survive multiple drive failures as long as at least one drive in each mirror survives.","A":"RAID 0 stripes data for performance but provides NO fault tolerance — any drive failure loses all data.","B":"RAID 1 mirrors data for fault tolerance but has no performance improvement and uses 50% of storage.","C":"RAID 5 stripes with distributed parity, tolerating one drive failure but with different performance characteristics.","D":"Correct. RAID 10 combines mirroring and striping for both fault tolerance and performance."}},
  {"id":202,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"A company stores backup copies in two geographically separate data centers in addition to the primary site. This follows which backup principle?","options":{"A":"3-2-1 rule","B":"GFS rotation","C":"Onsite backup","D":"Incremental-forever"},"correct_answer":"A","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"The 3-2-1 backup rule: keep at least 3 copies of data, on at least 2 different media types, with at least 1 copy stored offsite. Two separate data centers plus the primary satisfies the 3 copies and offsite requirements.","A":"Correct. 3 copies, 2 media types, 1 offsite is the 3-2-1 rule.","B":"GFS (Grandfather-Father-Son) is a backup rotation schedule, not a geographic distribution rule.","C":"Onsite backup describes a single location backup — the opposite of what is described.","D":"Incremental-forever is a backup strategy where incrementals never reset to a new full backup."}},
  {"id":203,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which data protection technique replaces sensitive data with realistic-looking but fake data for use in non-production environments?","options":{"A":"Tokenization","B":"Encryption","C":"Data masking","D":"Pseudonymization"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Data masking creates structurally similar but fictitious data for use in development, testing, and analytics. The masked data is realistic (correct format/length) but contains no real sensitive information.","A":"Tokenization replaces real data with tokens that can be mapped back to the original; masked data cannot be reversed.","B":"Encryption transforms data into ciphertext that can be decrypted; masking produces structurally valid fake data.","C":"Correct. Data masking produces realistic but fake data suitable for non-production use.","D":"Pseudonymization replaces identifying information with pseudonyms while keeping data usable; different from replacing with fake data."}},
  {"id":204,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which architecture model distributes application functions across multiple nodes without a single controlling authority?","options":{"A":"Centralized","B":"Decentralized","C":"Monolithic","D":"Serverless"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Decentralized architectures distribute processing and control across multiple nodes without a single point of control, improving resilience but complicating security management and policy enforcement.","A":"Centralized architectures have a single controlling authority — easier to secure but creates single points of failure.","B":"Correct. Decentralized architectures distribute control across multiple nodes.","C":"Monolithic architectures bundle all functions in one deployable unit; not about control distribution.","D":"Serverless refers to a cloud execution model, not a control distribution architecture."}},
  {"id":205,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which security configuration ensures that even if a firewall appliance fails, traffic is dropped rather than allowed through?","options":{"A":"Fail open","B":"High availability","C":"Fail closed (fail secure)","D":"Active-passive clustering"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Fail closed (fail secure) means the firewall drops all traffic if it fails, maintaining security at the cost of availability. This is the appropriate posture for security-critical devices.","A":"Fail open allows all traffic through on failure — sacrifices security for availability, appropriate for some non-security devices.","B":"High availability reduces the chance of failure by clustering but doesn't define the failure mode.","C":"Correct. Fail closed/secure drops traffic on failure, maintaining security posture.","D":"Active-passive clustering is an HA implementation; the failure mode behavior is still defined by fail open vs. closed."}},
  {"id":206,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which technology aggregates multiple WAN connections (broadband, LTE, MPLS) and uses software to optimize routing?","options":{"A":"MPLS","B":"SD-WAN","C":"SASE","D":"BGP"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"SD-WAN (Software-Defined Wide Area Network) uses software to manage and optimize traffic across multiple WAN connections, providing flexibility, cost savings, and centralized management.","A":"MPLS is a single WAN technology; SD-WAN aggregates multiple WAN types including MPLS.","B":"Correct. SD-WAN uses software to manage multiple WAN connections and optimize routing.","C":"SASE is a broader security framework that includes SD-WAN connectivity plus cloud security services.","D":"BGP is an internet routing protocol; SD-WAN uses BGP and other protocols as part of its operation."}},
  {"id":207,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which term describes sensitive data that is not formally classified by the organization but whose exposure would cause significant harm?","options":{"A":"Public data","B":"Shadow data","C":"Sensitive data","D":"Dark data"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Sensitive data is a general term for data requiring protection due to its nature (PII, PHI, financial data, trade secrets) even without formal classification labels.","A":"Public data is intentionally available to everyone; it requires no protection.","B":"Shadow data refers to data copies or backups that exist outside normal data governance.","C":"Correct. Sensitive data requires protection based on its content and potential harm from exposure.","D":"Dark data is collected but not analyzed or actively used; not specifically about sensitivity."}},
  {"id":208,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which type of DR test activates the actual backup site and operations, providing the most realistic test but with the highest risk?","options":{"A":"Tabletop exercise","B":"Parallel test","C":"Full interruption test","D":"Simulation"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"A full interruption test (also called a full cutover test) actually switches operations to the DR site, providing the most realistic validation but risking disruption if the DR site fails.","A":"A tabletop exercise is a discussion-based walkthrough with no actual system activity.","B":"A parallel test runs both primary and DR sites simultaneously; the primary site remains operational.","C":"Correct. Full interruption test activates DR operations by stopping the primary site — highest realism, highest risk.","D":"A simulation uses scenarios and injects without stopping actual operations."}},
  {"id":209,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which embedded system type must respond to events within guaranteed time constraints for real-time operations?","options":{"A":"General-purpose OS","B":"Real-Time Operating System (RTOS)","C":"Hypervisor","D":"Container runtime"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"An RTOS (Real-Time Operating System) guarantees response within defined time constraints, critical for applications like industrial control, medical devices, and vehicle systems where timing is safety-critical.","A":"General-purpose OSes (Windows, Linux) don't guarantee response times.","B":"Correct. RTOS provides deterministic, time-constrained responses required for real-time control systems.","C":"A hypervisor runs virtual machines; not related to real-time deterministic response.","D":"Container runtime manages containers; not designed for real-time deterministic operation."}},
  {"id":210,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Port 443 is blocked by a firewall rule. Which service would be MOST impacted?","options":{"A":"SSH","B":"DNS","C":"HTTPS","D":"SMTP"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":1,"explanations":{"correct":"Port 443 is the standard port for HTTPS (HTTP Secure). Blocking it prevents secure web browsing and all HTTPS-based services.","A":"SSH uses port 22.","B":"DNS uses port 53.","C":"Correct. HTTPS uses port 443; blocking it prevents secure web traffic.","D":"SMTP uses port 25 (or 587/465 for submission)."}},
  {"id":211,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which network security technology uses certificates and 802.1X to authenticate devices before allowing network access?","options":{"A":"VPN","B":"RADIUS with 802.1X","C":"MAC filtering","D":"DHCP reservation"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"802.1X provides port-based Network Access Control (NAC). Combined with RADIUS, it authenticates users and devices (using certificates, smart cards, or credentials) before granting network access at the switch/AP level.","A":"VPN authenticates remote users for secure tunnel access; it doesn't control local network port access.","B":"Correct. RADIUS with 802.1X provides certificate-based device authentication for network access.","C":"MAC filtering blocks/allows based on hardware addresses, which can be spoofed — not certificate-based.","D":"DHCP reservations assign specific IPs to devices; not an authentication mechanism."}},
  {"id":212,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which privacy concept limits the collection of personal data to only what is necessary for the specified purpose?","options":{"A":"Data sovereignty","B":"Data minimization","C":"Purpose limitation","D":"Data anonymization"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Data minimization is a privacy principle (key in GDPR) requiring that only data necessary for the specific purpose be collected — avoiding excess data collection that increases privacy risk.","A":"Data sovereignty addresses geographic data residency and applicable law.","B":"Correct. Data minimization limits collection to only what is necessary for the stated purpose.","C":"Purpose limitation restricts use of data to the originally stated purpose; minimization is about the amount collected.","D":"Data anonymization removes identifying information; not about limiting collection volume."}},
  {"id":213,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which power redundancy concept eliminates any single point of failure in power delivery to critical systems?","options":{"A":"UPS","B":"Generator","C":"Dual power supply with separate circuits","D":"Power conditioning"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Dual power supplies drawing from separate circuits (ideally on separate utility feeds) eliminates single points of failure. If one supply or circuit fails, the other continues to power the system.","A":"A UPS provides battery backup for brief outages but is a single system — still a potential single point of failure.","B":"A generator provides power during extended outages but doesn't eliminate single points of failure in normal delivery.","C":"Correct. Dual power supplies on separate circuits eliminate single points of failure in power delivery.","D":"Power conditioning filters electrical noise; it doesn't provide redundancy."}},
  {"id":214,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which cloud model is BEST suited for organizations that require multi-tenant architecture while needing higher security controls than public cloud?","options":{"A":"Public cloud","B":"Private cloud","C":"Hybrid cloud","D":"Community cloud"},"correct_answer":"D","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"A community cloud is shared among organizations with similar requirements (e.g., healthcare organizations sharing HIPAA-compliant infrastructure), providing a balance between public cloud cost efficiency and private cloud security controls.","A":"Public cloud is multi-tenant but has general-purpose security controls, not tailored to specific industry needs.","B":"Private cloud provides maximum control but is not multi-tenant.","C":"Hybrid cloud combines public and private but not specifically for same-industry multi-tenancy.","D":"Correct. Community clouds are shared among organizations with common security requirements."}},
  {"id":215,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which technique ensures that sensitive data is never stored in cloud provider logs or temporary files by encrypting client-side before upload?","options":{"A":"Server-side encryption","B":"Client-side encryption","C":"Transport encryption (TLS)","D":"Database encryption"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Client-side encryption encrypts data before it leaves the client's environment. The cloud provider only receives and stores ciphertext, with no access to plaintext or keys.","A":"Server-side encryption (SSE) encrypts data at the cloud provider; the provider manages keys and can theoretically access data.","B":"Correct. Client-side encryption ensures the provider never sees plaintext data.","C":"TLS protects data in transit but the cloud provider can access data once received.","D":"Database encryption protects data at rest in the database; the DB server can still access decrypted data during operations."}},
  {"id":216,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which data protection method replaces identifying information with artificial identifiers while maintaining data utility for analytics?","options":{"A":"Anonymization","B":"Pseudonymization","C":"Tokenization","D":"Masking"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Pseudonymization replaces direct identifiers with pseudonyms (artificial identifiers). Data can be re-linked to individuals using a separate key, maintaining utility while reducing privacy risk.","A":"Anonymization irreversibly removes identifying information so individuals cannot be re-identified.","B":"Correct. Pseudonymization replaces identifiers with pseudonyms that can be reversed with a key.","C":"Tokenization replaces data values with random tokens; in privacy context, pseudonymization is the more precise term.","D":"Masking partially obscures data; pseudonymization replaces identifiers with systematic substitutes."}},
  {"id":217,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which concept describes the total amount of planned downtime and unplanned downtime a system experiences in a given period?","options":{"A":"MTTR","B":"MTBF","C":"Availability","D":"RPO"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Availability is the percentage of time a system is operational. It accounts for all downtime (planned and unplanned) and is typically expressed as a percentage (e.g., 99.99% or 'four nines').","A":"MTTR (Mean Time To Repair) is the average time to restore a system after failure — one component of availability.","B":"MTBF (Mean Time Between Failures) measures the average time between system failures — another component.","C":"Correct. Availability is the overall measure of uptime versus total time.","D":"RPO defines maximum acceptable data loss in time; unrelated to system uptime measurement."}},
  {"id":218,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which configuration practice ensures router and switch management interfaces are only accessible from a dedicated management network segment?","options":{"A":"Defense in depth","B":"Out-of-band management","C":"Network segmentation","D":"Jump server"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Out-of-band (OOB) management uses a separate, dedicated network (management plane) for device administration, isolating management traffic from production traffic and reducing the management attack surface.","A":"Defense in depth layers controls; OOB management is a specific practice.","B":"Correct. Out-of-band management uses a separate network for device administration.","C":"Network segmentation divides networks but OOB specifically refers to the management plane separation.","D":"A jump server provides a controlled access point to management networks; OOB describes the separate management network itself."}},
  {"id":219,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"An employee emails a document with salary information to all staff by mistake. Which CIA property was violated?","options":{"A":"Integrity","B":"Availability","C":"Confidentiality","D":"Non-repudiation"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":1,"explanations":{"correct":"Sending salary information to unauthorized recipients violates confidentiality — sensitive data was disclosed to parties who should not have access to it.","A":"Integrity involves unauthorized modification; the document content was not altered.","B":"Availability concerns access to systems; the accidental disclosure does not affect availability.","C":"Correct. Unauthorized disclosure of sensitive information violates confidentiality.","D":"Non-repudiation is the inability to deny an action; it's not the property violated by disclosure."}},
  {"id":220,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Serverless computing introduces which unique security concern?","options":{"A":"Hypervisor vulnerabilities","B":"Function event injection","C":"VM escape","D":"Kernel exploitation"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":4,"explanations":{"correct":"Serverless functions execute in response to events. Attackers can inject malicious data through event triggers (file uploads, API calls, messages) that the function processes, enabling function-level code injection attacks.","A":"Hypervisor vulnerabilities affect VMs; serverless abstracts away the hypervisor entirely.","B":"Correct. Malicious event injection through triggers is the primary serverless-specific attack vector.","C":"VM escape exploits hypervisor isolation; serverless functions don't use traditional VMs.","D":"Kernel exploitation requires OS access; serverless functions have limited OS interaction."}},
  {"id":221,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which firewall rule action BEST matches 'drop all traffic that is not explicitly permitted'?","options":{"A":"Implicit allow","B":"Explicit deny","C":"Implicit deny","D":"Explicit allow"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Implicit deny (default deny) is a foundational firewall rule that blocks all traffic not explicitly permitted by other rules. It's the last rule in a firewall ruleset and is implied without being written.","A":"Implicit allow would allow everything not explicitly denied — the opposite, and insecure.","B":"Explicit deny writes a specific rule to deny specific traffic; implicit deny blocks everything remaining.","C":"Correct. Implicit deny blocks all traffic not explicitly permitted — the foundational firewall security principle.","D":"Explicit allow permits specific traffic; the last rule should be implicit deny."}},
  {"id":222,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which technology provides near-instant recovery by creating point-in-time images of storage systems that can be restored quickly?","options":{"A":"Cold backup","B":"Tape backup","C":"Storage snapshot","D":"Full disk encryption"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Storage snapshots capture the state of a storage system at a specific point in time. They enable fast recovery to a previous state, often in minutes, because they track block-level changes.","A":"Cold backups require full data restoration from offline media — much slower.","B":"Tape backups require mounting and reading sequential data — slow recovery.","C":"Correct. Snapshots enable rapid recovery to a point-in-time state.","D":"Full disk encryption protects data confidentiality; it does not enable recovery."}},
  {"id":223,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which approach requires organizations to know exactly what sensitive data they have, where it is stored, and who has access?","options":{"A":"Data minimization","B":"Data discovery and classification","C":"Data anonymization","D":"Data sovereignty"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Data discovery and classification involves identifying all data assets, categorizing them by sensitivity, and understanding their location, flow, and access — foundational for any data protection program.","A":"Data minimization limits data collection; it doesn't map existing data.","B":"Correct. Data discovery and classification identifies, locates, and categorizes data assets.","C":"Data anonymization removes identifying information; it requires knowing what data exists first.","D":"Data sovereignty addresses geographic storage rules; it depends on knowing where data is located."}},
  {"id":224,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"A load balancer distributes traffic across three web servers. If one server fails, traffic is automatically routed to the remaining servers. This provides:","options":{"A":"Confidentiality","B":"High availability","C":"Data integrity","D":"Non-repudiation"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":1,"explanations":{"correct":"A load balancer with automatic failover provides high availability — ensuring the service remains accessible even when individual servers fail, by distributing load across remaining healthy servers.","A":"Confidentiality is data protection from unauthorized access; load balancing addresses availability.","B":"Correct. Load balancing with failover provides high availability.","C":"Data integrity ensures data accuracy and consistency; not related to server load balancing.","D":"Non-repudiation ensures actions cannot be denied; unrelated to server load distribution."}},
  {"id":225,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which term describes the average time expected before a component fails?","options":{"A":"MTTR","B":"MTBF","C":"RPO","D":"RTO"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF) is the average time a component or system operates between failures. Higher MTBF indicates greater reliability.","A":"MTTR (Mean Time To Repair) is the average time to restore a system after it fails.","B":"Correct. MTBF measures the average time between failures, indicating reliability.","C":"RPO defines maximum acceptable data loss; not a reliability metric.","D":"RTO defines maximum allowed recovery time; not a reliability metric."}},
  {"id":226,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which deployment model provides the GREATEST flexibility for burst computing needs while maintaining sensitive data on-premises?","options":{"A":"Public cloud","B":"Private cloud","C":"Community cloud","D":"Hybrid cloud"},"correct_answer":"D","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Hybrid cloud combines private cloud (or on-premises) for sensitive workloads with public cloud for burst capacity. Organizations can scale to public cloud when needed while keeping sensitive data on-premises.","A":"Public cloud provides burst capacity but sensitive data is not kept on-premises.","B":"Private cloud keeps data on-premises but lacks the elastic burst capacity of public cloud.","C":"Community cloud is shared among similar organizations; doesn't specifically enable burst to public cloud.","D":"Correct. Hybrid cloud enables burst to public cloud while maintaining sensitive data on-premises."}},
  {"id":227,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which data state presents the greatest challenge to encryption because encryption would prevent the data from being used?","options":{"A":"Data at rest","B":"Data in transit","C":"Data in use","D":"Data in archive"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Data in use (being processed by CPU/RAM) must typically be in plaintext to be processed. Traditional encryption cannot protect data while it is actively being used without special techniques like homomorphic encryption.","A":"Data at rest can be encrypted and decrypted on demand without affecting normal use.","B":"Data in transit can be encrypted (TLS) and decrypted at endpoints without preventing use.","C":"Correct. Data in use must be decrypted to be processed, making it the hardest state to protect.","D":"Data in archive is a subset of data at rest and can be encrypted like other at-rest data."}},
  {"id":228,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which technology creates a secure network tunnel over the internet, encrypting all traffic between two endpoints?","options":{"A":"VLAN","B":"MPLS","C":"VPN","D":"SD-WAN"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":1,"explanations":{"correct":"A VPN (Virtual Private Network) creates an encrypted tunnel over the internet, allowing secure transmission of data between endpoints as if they were on the same private network.","A":"VLANs segment networks logically; they don't create encrypted tunnels.","B":"MPLS provides private WAN connectivity with QoS; it doesn't use internet encryption tunnels.","C":"Correct. VPN creates an encrypted tunnel over a public network.","D":"SD-WAN optimizes multi-WAN routing; it may use VPN tunnels but is not itself a VPN."}},
  {"id":229,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which DR strategy involves the ability to run critical workloads across multiple cloud providers to avoid vendor lock-in and single-provider outages?","options":{"A":"Multi-site","B":"Multi-cloud","C":"Hybrid cloud","D":"Geographic distribution"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Multi-cloud distributes workloads across multiple cloud providers (AWS, Azure, GCP), reducing dependency on any single provider and improving resilience against provider-specific outages.","A":"Multi-site refers to multiple geographic data centers; multi-cloud is specifically about multiple providers.","B":"Correct. Multi-cloud uses multiple cloud providers to avoid vendor lock-in and single-provider failures.","C":"Hybrid cloud combines on-premises and cloud; multi-cloud uses multiple cloud providers.","D":"Geographic distribution addresses location redundancy; multi-cloud is about provider redundancy."}},
  {"id":230,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"A web server in the DMZ receives a request for internal database data. The server is NOT allowed to directly query the database server. Which architectural principle does this enforce?","options":{"A":"Least functionality","B":"Defense in depth","C":"Separation of the application and data tiers","D":"Fail secure"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Separating the web/presentation tier in the DMZ from the database/data tier in the internal network enforces tiered architecture — the web server communicates through an application tier, not directly to the database.","A":"Least functionality disables unnecessary features; this is about network access boundaries between tiers.","B":"Defense in depth layers controls; the three-tier architecture is one application of this principle.","C":"Correct. Separating DMZ web servers from internal database servers enforces tier separation.","D":"Fail secure describes system behavior on failure, not architectural separation."}},
  {"id":231,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which security concern is MOST associated with container images pulled from public registries?","options":{"A":"Hypervisor vulnerabilities","B":"Malicious or vulnerable images in public registries","C":"Default credentials","D":"VM escape"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Public container registries may contain images with vulnerabilities, malware, or malicious code. Organizations must scan images before use and prefer trusted, verified sources.","A":"Containers don't use hypervisors in the traditional sense; this is a VM concern.","B":"Correct. Public registry images may contain unvetted, vulnerable, or malicious code.","C":"Default credentials are a runtime configuration issue, not specific to image source.","D":"VM escape is specific to hypervisor-based virtualization; containers use kernel-level isolation."}},
  {"id":232,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which security zone typically contains web servers that must be accessible from the internet while being isolated from internal systems?","options":{"A":"Internal LAN","B":"Management zone","C":"DMZ (Demilitarized Zone)","D":"Trusted zone"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":1,"explanations":{"correct":"The DMZ hosts internet-facing services (web servers, email gateways, DNS) with firewalls between the internet and DMZ, and between the DMZ and internal network, isolating public services from internal systems.","A":"The internal LAN hosts private resources accessible only from within the organization.","B":"The management zone provides secure administrative access to network devices.","C":"Correct. The DMZ hosts internet-facing services while isolating them from the internal network.","D":"Trusted zone refers to the internal network where full trust is extended to internal resources."}},
  {"id":233,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Under GDPR, which rights allow individuals to request their data be deleted from an organization's systems?","options":{"A":"Right to access","B":"Right to erasure (right to be forgotten)","C":"Right to portability","D":"Right to restriction"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"The right to erasure ('right to be forgotten') under GDPR allows individuals to request deletion of their personal data under specific circumstances, such as when the data is no longer necessary for the purpose it was collected.","A":"Right to access allows individuals to request a copy of their personal data.","B":"Correct. The right to erasure allows individuals to request deletion of their personal data.","C":"Right to portability allows receiving data in a machine-readable format for transfer to another controller.","D":"Right to restriction limits how an organization processes personal data while a dispute is resolved."}},
  {"id":234,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"During a continuity of operations planning exercise, the team identifies which critical business functions must continue during a disruption. This process is called:","options":{"A":"Risk assessment","B":"Business Impact Analysis (BIA)","C":"Tabletop exercise","D":"Gap analysis"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"A Business Impact Analysis (BIA) identifies critical business functions, assesses the impact of disruptions on those functions, and establishes recovery priorities, RTOs, and RPOs for continuity planning.","A":"Risk assessment identifies threats and vulnerabilities; BIA focuses on business impact and recovery priorities.","B":"Correct. BIA identifies critical functions and the impact of disruptions, driving recovery planning.","C":"A tabletop exercise tests response procedures through discussion; BIA is the analysis phase.","D":"Gap analysis identifies differences between current and desired states; BIA analyzes disruption impacts."}},
  {"id":235,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which configuration change BEST reduces the attack surface of a Linux server?","options":{"A":"Enable all services for maximum functionality","B":"Disable unused services and uninstall unnecessary packages","C":"Open all inbound firewall rules","D":"Enable telnet for remote management"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":1,"explanations":{"correct":"Disabling unused services and removing unnecessary packages follows the principle of least functionality — every additional service is a potential attack vector.","A":"Enabling all services maximizes the attack surface, the opposite of hardening.","B":"Correct. Disabling unused services and removing unnecessary software reduces the attack surface.","C":"Opening all firewall rules removes network protection.","D":"Telnet transmits credentials in plaintext; SSH should be used instead."}},
  {"id":236,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which term describes a hardware device with a fixed function embedded into firmware that cannot be easily changed?","options":{"A":"Virtual machine","B":"Container","C":"Embedded system","D":"Thin client"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Embedded systems are computing devices with hardware and software designed for a specific dedicated function, typically with firmware that is difficult to update — found in IoT devices, medical equipment, routers, and industrial control systems.","A":"Virtual machines run software-defined environments on shared hardware.","B":"Containers package application code and dependencies; they run on general-purpose OSes.","C":"Correct. Embedded systems have fixed, dedicated functions implemented in hardware/firmware.","D":"Thin clients are minimal computers that rely on server-side processing; they are general-purpose terminals."}},
  {"id":237,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which data handling practice limits how long an organization may retain personal data?","options":{"A":"Data sovereignty","B":"Data retention policy","C":"Right to erasure","D":"Data minimization"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"A data retention policy defines how long different categories of data must be kept and when they must be deleted, balancing legal/regulatory requirements with privacy obligations.","A":"Data sovereignty addresses geographic jurisdiction; not about retention duration.","B":"Correct. Data retention policies define how long data is kept before it must be deleted.","C":"Right to erasure allows individuals to request deletion; retention policies define organizational timelines.","D":"Data minimization limits the amount of data collected; retention limits how long it is kept."}},
  {"id":238,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which RAID level uses a parity drive to allow recovery from a single disk failure?","options":{"A":"RAID 0","B":"RAID 1","C":"RAID 5","D":"RAID 6"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"RAID 5 distributes parity information across all drives. If one drive fails, data can be reconstructed from the remaining drives and parity. It tolerates one drive failure.","A":"RAID 0 stripes data with no fault tolerance — any drive failure is catastrophic.","B":"RAID 1 mirrors drives; it doesn't use parity.","C":"Correct. RAID 5 uses distributed parity to tolerate one drive failure.","D":"RAID 6 uses double parity to tolerate two simultaneous drive failures."}},
  {"id":239,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"A company requires all remote employee traffic to be routed through the corporate network security stack before reaching the internet. This is called:","options":{"A":"Split tunneling","B":"Full tunnel VPN","C":"SSL inspection","D":"NAT"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Full tunnel VPN routes all traffic (including internet-bound) through the corporate VPN to be inspected by security controls before reaching the internet, ensuring uniform policy enforcement.","A":"Split tunneling only routes corporate traffic through the VPN; internet traffic bypasses it.","B":"Correct. Full tunnel VPN routes all traffic through the corporate security stack.","C":"SSL inspection decrypts and inspects HTTPS traffic; not related to VPN tunnel type.","D":"NAT translates private to public IP addresses; not the same as VPN tunnel configuration."}},
  {"id":240,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which connectivity type for IoT devices uses short-range radio waves and is commonly used for point-of-sale systems and contactless payments?","options":{"A":"Bluetooth","B":"Wi-Fi","C":"NFC (Near Field Communication)","D":"Zigbee"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"NFC operates at 13.56 MHz with a range of ~10cm, making it ideal for contactless payment and access cards. Its extremely short range limits some attack vectors but requires proximity.","A":"Bluetooth has a range of up to 100m and is used for peripheral devices, not contactless payment.","B":"Wi-Fi has a range of tens to hundreds of meters and is used for network connectivity.","C":"Correct. NFC's very short range makes it suitable for contactless payment and access control.","D":"Zigbee is a low-power mesh protocol used in home automation; not typical for payment systems."}},
  {"id":241,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"After a disaster recovery event, which document outlines how the organization will transition back from the alternate site to normal operations?","options":{"A":"Business continuity plan (BCP)","B":"Disaster recovery plan (DRP)","C":"Reconstitution plan","D":"Incident response plan (IRP)"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"A reconstitution plan (also called restoration plan) defines the process of transitioning from the alternate/DR site back to the primary site or new permanent location after a disaster.","A":"The BCP maintains critical business functions during a disruption; reconstitution is the return to normal.","B":"The DRP focuses on restoring IT systems; reconstitution covers the full return-to-normal process.","C":"Correct. The reconstitution plan covers the transition back from DR operations to normal operations.","D":"The IRP handles security incidents; reconstitution is a DR/BCP process."}},
  {"id":242,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which network device collects traffic from multiple switch ports and sends a copy to a monitoring device without affecting network performance?","options":{"A":"Load balancer","B":"Network TAP or SPAN port","C":"Proxy server","D":"IPS"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Network TAPs (Test Access Points) and SPAN (Switched Port Analyzer) ports copy network traffic to a monitoring device (IDS, SIEM) without affecting the production traffic flow.","A":"Load balancers distribute traffic across servers; they don't copy traffic for monitoring.","B":"Correct. TAPs and SPAN ports copy network traffic to monitoring devices without affecting production.","C":"Proxy servers intermediate connections; they don't copy traffic for passive monitoring.","D":"IPS devices sit inline and inspect/block traffic; they are not passive monitoring tools."}},
  {"id":243,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"A healthcare organization must protect patient information. Which regulation defines specific requirements for protecting health information in the US?","options":{"A":"GDPR","B":"PCI DSS","C":"HIPAA","D":"SOX"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":1,"explanations":{"correct":"HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) establishes US federal standards for protecting Protected Health Information (PHI) and requires appropriate administrative, physical, and technical safeguards.","A":"GDPR is a European Union regulation for personal data protection; it applies globally to EU residents' data but is not US healthcare-specific.","B":"PCI DSS applies to payment card data; not healthcare records.","C":"Correct. HIPAA specifically regulates the protection of health information in the US.","D":"SOX (Sarbanes-Oxley) applies to financial reporting for publicly traded companies; not healthcare."}},
  {"id":244,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which cloud security concern occurs when data stored by one customer can be accessed by another customer due to improper isolation?","options":{"A":"Data sovereignty","B":"Multitenancy risk","C":"Vendor lock-in","D":"API vulnerability"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Multitenancy risk arises in cloud environments where multiple customers share the same physical or virtual infrastructure. Insufficient isolation could allow one tenant to access another's data.","A":"Data sovereignty concerns geographic data residency, not tenant isolation.","B":"Correct. Multitenancy risk is the failure to properly isolate data between shared tenants.","C":"Vendor lock-in is the difficulty of migrating away from a cloud provider; not a data isolation issue.","D":"API vulnerabilities affect specific API endpoints; multitenancy risk is broader isolation concern."}},
  {"id":245,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which concept describes an organization's ability to continue operations during a disruption while recovery proceeds?","options":{"A":"Disaster recovery","B":"Incident response","C":"Business continuity","D":"Crisis management"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Business continuity focuses on maintaining essential business functions during a disruption, not just recovering IT systems. It encompasses all aspects of keeping the business operational.","A":"Disaster recovery specifically addresses restoring IT systems and data; business continuity is broader.","B":"Incident response addresses security events; business continuity is about operational resilience.","C":"Correct. Business continuity ensures critical operations continue during disruptions.","D":"Crisis management deals with the human and communications aspects of a crisis; business continuity is the operational plan."}},
  {"id":246,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which secure network design practice uses a 'jump server' or 'bastion host'?","options":{"A":"To distribute web traffic across multiple servers","B":"To provide a single, hardened access point for administrative access to protected systems","C":"To monitor all internal network traffic","D":"To terminate VPN connections from remote users"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"A jump server (bastion host) is a hardened, heavily audited server that serves as the sole gateway for administrative access to sensitive systems. All admin connections must pass through it, centralizing access control and logging.","A":"Distributing web traffic is the role of a load balancer.","B":"Correct. A jump server provides a single, audited access point for administrative connections to protected systems.","C":"Monitoring network traffic is the role of SIEM, IDS, or packet capture tools.","D":"VPN connection termination is handled by VPN gateways or concentrators."}},
  {"id":247,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which cryptographic technique allows a verifier to confirm that data has not been altered without revealing the actual data?","options":{"A":"Symmetric encryption","B":"Asymmetric encryption","C":"Cryptographic hashing","D":"Digital signature"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Cryptographic hashing produces a fixed-length digest from any input. If data changes, the hash changes. A verifier can compute the hash of received data and compare it to the expected hash without seeing the original data.","A":"Symmetric encryption protects confidentiality; it doesn't verify integrity without decryption.","B":"Asymmetric encryption and digital signatures verify integrity and authenticity; hashing alone verifies integrity without exposing data.","C":"Correct. Hashing verifies data integrity without exposing the data itself.","D":"Digital signatures use hashing plus asymmetric encryption for non-repudiation; hashing alone provides integrity checking."}},
  {"id":248,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which term describes the hardware-level security feature that verifies the integrity of the boot process to ensure no tampering occurred before the OS loads?","options":{"A":"Secure boot","B":"UEFI","C":"TPM","D":"HSM"},"correct_answer":"A","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Secure Boot is a UEFI feature that verifies the digital signatures of boot loaders and OS kernels before execution, ensuring only trusted, signed software runs during the boot process.","A":"Correct. Secure Boot validates boot software signatures to prevent unauthorized code from running at startup.","B":"UEFI is the firmware interface that replaced BIOS; Secure Boot is a feature within UEFI.","C":"A TPM (Trusted Platform Module) stores cryptographic keys and can be used by Secure Boot, but TPM itself is a hardware chip, not the boot integrity verification feature.","D":"An HSM (Hardware Security Module) is a dedicated cryptographic device for key management; not for boot verification."}},
  {"id":249,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which approach to capacity planning ensures systems can scale up to handle demand spikes without manual intervention?","options":{"A":"Manual scaling","B":"Scheduled scaling","C":"Auto-scaling","D":"Over-provisioning"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Auto-scaling automatically adds or removes resources based on demand metrics (CPU, traffic), handling peaks without human intervention and optimizing cost during low-demand periods.","A":"Manual scaling requires human action to add resources — too slow for sudden demand spikes.","B":"Scheduled scaling adds resources at predetermined times; it can't respond to unpredicted spikes.","C":"Correct. Auto-scaling dynamically adjusts resources based on real-time demand.","D":"Over-provisioning permanently allocates excess resources; it handles spikes but wastes resources."}},
  {"id":250,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"DNS Security Extensions (DNSSEC) primarily protects against which attack?","options":{"A":"DDoS against DNS servers","B":"DNS cache poisoning and zone data spoofing","C":"DNS tunneling","D":"Domain typosquatting"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to validate DNS records, ensuring responses are authentic and have not been tampered with. It directly prevents cache poisoning attacks where forged DNS records redirect users to malicious sites.","A":"DNSSEC doesn't protect against DDoS; rate limiting and AnyCast mitigate DNS DDoS.","B":"Correct. DNSSEC validates DNS response authenticity, preventing cache poisoning.","C":"DNS tunneling abuses the DNS protocol for data exfiltration; DNSSEC doesn't prevent it.","D":"Typosquatting registers fake domains; DNSSEC can't prevent legitimate registration of lookalike domains."}},
  {"id":251,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"A cloud-based service inspects and controls data moving between an organization and cloud applications, enforcing security policies. This is a:","options":{"A":"WAF","B":"CASB (Cloud Access Security Broker)","C":"Firewall","D":"DLP"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"A CASB (Cloud Access Security Broker) sits between users and cloud service providers, enforcing security policies, providing visibility, preventing data leakage, and detecting threats in cloud usage.","A":"A WAF protects web applications from attacks at the application layer; not focused on cloud service policy enforcement.","B":"Correct. A CASB enforces security policies for cloud service access and data movement.","C":"A traditional firewall controls network traffic based on IP/port; it doesn't understand cloud application context.","D":"DLP prevents data exfiltration; CASB is broader, providing visibility and control across cloud services including DLP capabilities."}},
  {"id":252,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which backup media type provides the highest capacity and lowest cost per gigabyte for long-term archival?","options":{"A":"SSD","B":"HDD","C":"Magnetic tape","D":"Cloud storage"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Magnetic tape has the lowest cost per gigabyte and highest capacity per cartridge, making it the most economical choice for long-term archival despite slow access times.","A":"SSDs are fast but expensive per gigabyte; not suitable for large archival.","B":"HDDs offer good capacity at reasonable cost but are more expensive per GB than tape for archival.","C":"Correct. Magnetic tape provides the lowest cost per GB for long-term archival storage.","D":"Cloud storage costs vary but ongoing monthly fees can exceed tape costs for very long-term archival."}},
  {"id":253,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which network security control prevents unauthorized access to switch ports by limiting which MAC addresses can communicate?","options":{"A":"VLAN segmentation","B":"Port security","C":"DHCP snooping","D":"802.1X"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Switch port security limits the number and identity of MAC addresses allowed on a port, preventing unauthorized devices from connecting. Violations can trigger port shutdown.","A":"VLAN segmentation divides networks logically; it doesn't restrict specific MAC addresses on a port.","B":"Correct. Port security limits MAC addresses per switch port, preventing unauthorized device connections.","C":"DHCP snooping filters rogue DHCP servers; not specifically MAC address restriction.","D":"802.1X authenticates devices via credentials/certificates; port security is a simpler MAC-based control."}},
  {"id":254,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which strategy ensures that personally identifiable information (PII) cannot be traced back to an individual, even when combined with other datasets?","options":{"A":"Pseudonymization","B":"Tokenization","C":"Anonymization","D":"Data masking"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Anonymization irreversibly removes or transforms personal identifiers so that individuals cannot be re-identified even when the data is combined with other available datasets. Unlike pseudonymization, there is no key for re-identification.","A":"Pseudonymization replaces identifiers with pseudonyms but can be reversed with a key.","B":"Tokenization substitutes data with tokens; original data can be recovered from the vault.","C":"Correct. Anonymization permanently removes re-identification capability.","D":"Data masking partially conceals data but the original format/structure may still allow re-identification."}},
  {"id":255,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which communication method between microservices exposes functions over HTTP and is a common attack surface for APIs?","options":{"A":"Direct memory access","B":"REST API","C":"IPC (Inter-process communication)","D":"Shared database"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"REST APIs use HTTP/HTTPS as the communication protocol between microservices. This exposes API endpoints that are subject to web-based attacks (injection, broken authentication, BOLA/IDOR), making API security a critical concern.","A":"Direct memory access is hardware-level; microservices communicate via network protocols.","B":"Correct. REST APIs over HTTP are the primary communication method and attack surface for microservices.","C":"IPC is used within a single process/system; microservices communicate over networks.","D":"Shared databases between microservices violate the microservices principle of independent data stores."}},
  {"id":256,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which geographic factor should be considered when selecting a secondary data center location for disaster recovery?","options":{"A":"Proximity to the primary site for low latency","B":"Sufficient distance to avoid the same natural disaster affecting both sites","C":"Same power grid as the primary site","D":"Same network provider as the primary site"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"A secondary DR site must be geographically distant enough to not be affected by the same regional disaster (earthquake, hurricane, flood). Being too close defeats the purpose of geographic redundancy.","A":"Proximity to the primary reduces latency for replication but also risks both sites being in the same disaster zone.","B":"Correct. Geographic separation protects against regional disasters affecting both sites simultaneously.","C":"Using the same power grid means a regional grid failure could affect both sites.","D":"Using the same network provider creates a single point of failure in connectivity."}},
  {"id":257,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"An organization deploys honeypots and fake DNS entries to detect and confuse attackers. Which broad strategy does this represent?","options":{"A":"Defense in depth","B":"Deceptive security / active defense","C":"Zero trust","D":"Least privilege"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Deceptive security (active defense) uses fake assets, honeypots, honey tokens, and deceptive DNS entries to detect attackers, slow them down, and gather threat intelligence.","A":"Defense in depth layers security controls; deception is one specific strategy within it.","B":"Correct. Using honeypots and fake entries to detect and deceive attackers is active/deceptive defense.","C":"Zero trust eliminates implicit trust and verifies access; it does not involve deception.","D":"Least privilege restricts access rights; not related to deception."}},
  {"id":258,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"Which standard primarily governs the protection of payment card data?","options":{"A":"HIPAA","B":"GDPR","C":"PCI DSS","D":"SOX"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":1,"explanations":{"correct":"PCI DSS (Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard) defines security requirements for organizations that process, store, or transmit credit and debit card information.","A":"HIPAA governs health information in the US; not payment card data.","B":"GDPR governs personal data of EU residents; not specifically payment card security.","C":"Correct. PCI DSS specifically addresses payment card data security.","D":"SOX governs financial reporting for publicly traded companies; not payment card data."}},
  {"id":259,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which wireless security protocol is recommended for enterprise networks and uses 802.1X authentication?","options":{"A":"WEP","B":"WPA2-Personal (PSK)","C":"WPA2/WPA3-Enterprise","D":"WPS"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"WPA2/WPA3-Enterprise uses 802.1X authentication with a RADIUS server, providing individual user credentials instead of a shared passphrase, enabling per-user accounting and revocation.","A":"WEP is deprecated and broken — RC4 encryption with severe vulnerabilities.","B":"WPA2-Personal (PSK) uses a shared passphrase, not individual credentials — suitable for home/small networks.","C":"Correct. WPA2/WPA3-Enterprise with 802.1X provides individual authentication for enterprise networks.","D":"WPS is a convenience feature with known vulnerabilities (PIN brute force) and should be disabled."}},
  {"id":260,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which power protection device provides continuous power from batteries, bridging the gap between utility failure and generator startup?","options":{"A":"PDU","B":"UPS","C":"Generator","D":"Surge protector"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":1,"explanations":{"correct":"A UPS (Uninterruptible Power Supply) provides instantaneous battery backup when utility power fails, allowing time for graceful shutdown or for a generator to start and stabilize.","A":"A PDU (Power Distribution Unit) distributes power to equipment; it doesn't provide backup power.","B":"Correct. A UPS provides immediate battery power during outages until generators start.","C":"A generator provides extended backup power but takes seconds to minutes to start — not instantaneous.","D":"A surge protector filters voltage spikes; it doesn't provide backup power."}},
  {"id":261,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"What does the principle of 'least functionality' mean when applied to network devices?","options":{"A":"Using the cheapest devices available","B":"Configuring devices with only necessary features and services enabled","C":"Deploying a single device for multiple functions","D":"Using minimal encryption to maximize performance"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Least functionality means configuring systems and devices with only the features, services, and protocols necessary for their intended purpose, disabling or removing everything else to minimize the attack surface.","A":"Cost is not the principle; functionality limitation is about security, not budget.","B":"Correct. Least functionality enables only necessary features, minimizing the attack surface.","C":"Multi-function devices can increase attack surface; least functionality addresses configuration.","D":"Encryption should be as strong as needed; least functionality doesn't mean weak encryption."}},
  {"id":262,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.3","objective":"Compare and contrast concepts and strategies to protect data","stem":"A company performs a 'Data Protection Impact Assessment' before launching a new service that processes personal data. This is required by:","options":{"A":"PCI DSS","B":"HIPAA","C":"GDPR","D":"SOX"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"GDPR (Article 35) requires a Data Protection Impact Assessment (DPIA) before processing activities likely to result in high risk to individuals' rights, particularly new technologies or large-scale personal data processing.","A":"PCI DSS requires risk assessments for payment card environments; not DPIAs for new services.","B":"HIPAA requires Privacy Impact Assessments for some activities but uses different terminology.","C":"Correct. GDPR requires DPIAs for high-risk processing activities.","D":"SOX addresses financial reporting controls; not personal data processing assessments."}},
  {"id":263,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.1","objective":"Compare and contrast security implications of different architecture models","stem":"Which advantage does containerization offer over traditional virtual machines from a security perspective?","options":{"A":"Containers provide stronger isolation than VMs","B":"Containers have a smaller attack surface due to lighter weight OS dependencies","C":"Containers cannot be compromised once deployed","D":"Containers encrypt all data by default"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":3,"explanations":{"correct":"Containers share the host kernel and have minimal OS overhead, reducing the number of packages and components that could be vulnerable compared to full VMs with their own guest OSes.","A":"VMs provide stronger isolation than containers because each VM has its own kernel; container isolation relies on kernel namespaces.","B":"Correct. Containers have fewer OS components than VMs, reducing the potential attack surface.","C":"Containers can be compromised; they are not inherently immune.","D":"Containers don't encrypt data by default; encryption must be implemented separately."}},
  {"id":264,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.4","objective":"Explain the importance of resilience and recovery","stem":"Which continuity strategy involves documenting and regularly testing manual procedures that can be used if automated systems become unavailable?","options":{"A":"Hot standby","B":"Manual fallback procedures","C":"Parallel processing","D":"Geographic redundancy"},"correct_answer":"B","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Manual fallback procedures document how critical processes can be performed manually when automated systems are unavailable, ensuring the organization can continue minimal operations during IT outages.","A":"Hot standby provides immediate automated failover to a duplicate system; not manual procedures.","B":"Correct. Manual fallback procedures enable operations without automated systems.","C":"Parallel processing runs primary and secondary systems simultaneously; not the same as manual procedures.","D":"Geographic redundancy addresses site-level availability; manual procedures address system-level contingencies."}},
  {"id":265,"domain":3,"subdomain":"3.2","objective":"Apply security principles to secure enterprise infrastructure","stem":"Which security principle should guide the default stance of a network access control system?","options":{"A":"Trust all internal traffic","B":"Allow by default, log exceptions","C":"Deny by default, allow explicitly","D":"Allow all encrypted traffic"},"correct_answer":"C","difficulty":2,"explanations":{"correct":"Deny by default (default deny) is the fundamental security stance — block all access unless explicitly permitted. This ensures only intended traffic is allowed, aligning with least privilege for network access.","A":"Trusting all internal traffic is a legacy perimeter model; zero trust rejects this approach.","B":"Allow by default creates an insecure posture where every threat must be explicitly blocked.","C":"Correct. Deny by default with explicit allows is the secure baseline for access control.","D":"Allowing all encrypted traffic ignores the content and intent of the traffic."}},
]
